For a prime `p ≤ √n`, we can use Legendre's formula which tells us that the exponent of `p` in `n!` is `∑_{k=1}^∞ floor(n/p^k)`. Since our initial factorization has size `n`, we can expect the sum of `p`-adic valuations to be related to `n/p + n/p^2 + ...`.

